LONDON &#8211; BlackRock remains positive on South African bonds despite signs of tensions within the government, the head of emerging debt at the world&#8217;s largest asset manager said on Wednesday, adding that investors would have to &#8220;live with&#8221; political noise.South African assets have sold off heavily this week on speculation the country&#8217;s finance minister would be removed from his post. Pravin Gordhan was ordered back home from an investor roadshow by President Jacob Zuma on Monday.But BlackRock&#8217;s Sergio Trigo Paz said he remained &#8220;long&#8221; on South African debt, noting that the central bank has room to cut interest rates. &#8220;There will be noise in South Africa but we will have to live with it,&#8221; Trigo Paz told a briefing in London.